The rollover funds of the cancelled 2020 hajj will be deposited in the Hajj Saving Scheme,the chairman of the National Hajj Commission of Nigeria (NAHCON), Alhaji  Zikrullah Kunle Hassan, has said He disclosed this yesterday while briefing newsmen in Abuja. According to him, the 2021 Hajj registration would commence on September 9, 2020. He, however, said that any intending pilgrim who desires to recover his or her deposit for the 2020 Hajj which was cancelled due to the coronavirus pandemic would be refunded through his or her bank account. Hassan said that the intending pilgrims who may wish to leave or rollover their deposit for 2021 Hajj would be accorded priority and right of first refusal in 2021 Hajj registration. “Any intending pilgrim who desires to recover his/her deposit shall be refunded his money. However, those who may wish to leave or rollover their deposit for 2021 Hajj shall be accorded the highest priority and right of first refusal in 2021 Hajj. “The commission will commence Hajj registration for 2021 from September 9, 2020. In the light of this, the e-Hajj portal for pilgrims’ registration will be opened immediately. Further guidelines will be issued in due course. “The commission has begun a transformation journey to the digital world – a strategic transformation plan (2020-2024) in which our idea will be driven by technological innovation. “The rollover funds will be deposited in the Hajj Saving Scheme which will soon take off,” Hassan said. He said the refund of the 2020 Hajj deposit would be done through a bank account and advised intending pilgrims who wish to collect their deposit to open an account through which the money will be paid. NAHCOM boss while reiterating his vows to make Hajj affordable for intending pilgrims across the country, said the much awaited Hajj Saving Scheme would make the cost of Hajj affordable in the near future.